<H1><A NAME="SECTION00050000000000000000">
FRT-Construction</A>
</H1>

<P>
The <IMG
 WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img177.png"
 ALT="$r$"> fold tensor product of <IMG
 WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img5.png"
 ALT="$V$"> is denoted by <IMG
 WIDTH="37" HEIGHT="20" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img178.png"
 ALT="$V^{\otimes r}$">. Since
it is a free <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">-module, as well, we may apply all results of
former sections to a situation where <IMG
 WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img5.png"
 ALT="$V$"> is substituted by <IMG
 WIDTH="37" HEIGHT="20" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img178.png"
 ALT="$V^{\otimes r}$">,
<IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img9.png"
 ALT="${\cal E}$"> by <!-- MATH
 ${\cal E}_r:={\rm End}_{R}{(V^{\otimes r})}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="38" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img179.png"
 ALT="${\cal E}_r:={\rm End}_{R}{(V^{\otimes r})}$"> and <IMG
 WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img14.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}}^*$"> by
<!-- MATH
 ${{\cal E}_r}^*:={\rm Hom}_{R}{({\cal E}_r,R)}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="165" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img180.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}_r}^*:={\rm Hom}_{R}{({\cal E}_r,R)}$">. There are
natural isomorphisms between <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img181.png"
 ALT="${\cal E}_r$"> and
<!-- MATH
 ${{\cal E}}^{\otimes r}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="34" HEIGHT="20" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img182.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}}^{\otimes r}$"> and between <!-- MATH
 ${{\cal E}_r}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img183.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}_r}^*$"> and <!-- MATH
 ${{{\cal E}}^*}^{\otimes r}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="42" HEIGHT="21" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img184.png"
 ALT="${{{\cal E}}^*}^{\otimes r}$">. We will omit
them in our notation and consider them as identity maps. Set
<!-- MATH
 $V^{\otimes 0}:={\cal E}_{0}:=R$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="39" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img185.png"
 ALT="$V^{\otimes 0}:={\cal E}_{0}:=R$">.
<BR>
<P>
Suppose we are given a family 
<!-- MATH
 ${\cal A}=({\cal A}_r)_{r \in {\mathbb{N}}_0}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="114" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img186.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}=({\cal A}_r)_{r \in {\mathbb{N}}_0}$"> of <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">-algebras
such that <!-- MATH
 ${\cal A}_r\subseteq {\cal E}_r$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img187.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}_r\subseteq {\cal E}_r$">. According to lemma <A HREF="node2.html#Koideal">2.1</A>
there is an associated family of coideals <IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img188.png"
 ALT="$K_r$"> in <!-- MATH
 ${{\cal E}_r}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img183.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}_r}^*$">. 

<P>
<BR>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER"><A NAME="homogene_Koideale"></A>
<!-- MATH
 \begin{eqnarray}
K_r:=K({\cal A}_r).
\end{eqnarray}
 -->
<TABLE ALIGN="CENTER" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR VALIGN="MIDDLE"><TD NOWRAP ALIGN="RIGHT"><IMG
 WIDTH="118" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img189.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle K_r:=K({\cal A}_r).$"></TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10 ALIGN="RIGHT">
(9)</TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL"><P></P>

<P>
By the above identification we consider <!-- MATH
 ${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*):=\bigoplus_{r \in
{\mathbb{N}}_0}{{\cal E}_r}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img190.png"
 ALT="${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*):=\bigoplus_{r \in
{\mathbb{N}}_0}{{\cal E}_r}^*$"> as the tensor algebra on the <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">-module <IMG
 WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img14.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}}^*$">.
There is a unique coalgebra structure on this tensor algebra, extending
the one from <IMG
 WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img14.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}}^*$"> and turning <!-- MATH
 ${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img191.png"
 ALT="${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$"> into a bialgebra.
Furthermore the <!-- MATH
 ${{\cal E}_r}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img183.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}_r}^*$"> are subcoalgebras dual to the algebras
<IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img181.png"
 ALT="${\cal E}_r$">, i.e. the coalgebra structure on <!-- MATH
 ${{\cal E}_r}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img183.png"
 ALT="${{\cal E}_r}^*$"> is the one considered
above.
Epimorphic images of this bialgebra are called <EM>matric bialgebras</EM>
(cf. [<A
 HREF="node9.html#tak2">Ta</A>]).
Let us investigate under what circumstances the coideal
<BR>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER"><A NAME="Def._I"></A>
<!-- MATH
 \begin{eqnarray}
I:=\oplus_{r \in {\mathbb{N}}_0 } K_r
\end{eqnarray}
 -->
<TABLE ALIGN="CENTER" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR VALIGN="MIDDLE"><TD NOWRAP ALIGN="RIGHT"><IMG
 WIDTH="115" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img192.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle I:=\oplus_{r \in {\mathbb{N}}_0 } K_r$"></TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10 ALIGN="RIGHT">
(10)</TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL"><P></P>
becomes an ideal in <!-- MATH
 ${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img191.png"
 ALT="${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$"> and thus consequently is a
biideal. To this claim we consider inclusion maps
<!-- MATH
 $s_{r},t_{r}:{\cal E}_r\rightarrow {\cal E}_{r+1}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="141" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img193.png"
 ALT="$s_{r},t_{r}:{\cal E}_r\rightarrow {\cal E}_{r+1}$"> given by
<BR><P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
s_{r}(\mu )=\mu \otimes {\rm id}_{V}, \; t_{r}(\mu )={\rm id}_{V}\otimes \mu ,\; \mu 
\in {\cal E}_r
\end{displaymath}
 -->

<IMG
 WIDTH="446" HEIGHT="33" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img194.png"
 ALT="\begin{displaymath}
s_{r}(\mu )=\mu \otimes {\rm id}_{V}, \; t_{r}(\mu )={\rm id}_{V}\otimes \mu ,\; \mu
\in {\cal E}_r\end{displaymath}">
</DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL">
<P></P>
and focus attention to a special situation, which is general enough
for our applications.  We start with an arbitrary subset
<!-- MATH
 $N\subseteq {\cal E}_{2}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="65" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img195.png"
 ALT="$N\subseteq {\cal E}_{2}$"> and define a family <IMG
 WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img196.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}$"> inductively beginning with
<!-- MATH
 ${\cal A}_{0}:=R,\; {\cal A}_{1}:=R\cdot{\rm id}_{V}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="194" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img197.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}_{0}:=R,\; {\cal A}_{1}:=R\cdot{\rm id}_{V}$"> and <IMG
 WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img198.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}_{2}$"> as the
algebraic span of <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img56.png"
 ALT="$N$"> in <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img199.png"
 ALT="${\cal E}_{2}$">, than continuing by the formula
<BR><P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
{\cal A}_r:=\left<s_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1}) +
t_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1})\right>_{\rm Alg} \;\;\mbox{ for } \;\;r>2.
\end{displaymath}
 -->

<IMG
 WIDTH="475" HEIGHT="36" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img200.png"
 ALT="\begin{displaymath}{\cal A}_r:=\left&lt;s_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1}) +
t_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1})\right&gt;_{\rm Alg} \;\;\mbox{ for } \;\;r&gt;2.\end{displaymath}">
</DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL">
<P></P>
We call this a <EM>by <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img56.png"
 ALT="$N$"> induced family</EM> of subalgebras of <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img181.png"
 ALT="${\cal E}_r$">.

<P>
<P>
<DIV><A NAME="Biideal"><B>Proposition  5.1</B></A> &nbsp; 
Let <IMG
 WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img196.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}$"> be the family induced by a subset <!-- MATH
 $N\subseteq
{\cal E}_{2}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="65" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img195.png"
 ALT="$N\subseteq {\cal E}_{2}$">. Then the coideal <IMG
 WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img201.png"
 ALT="$I$"> defined in (<A HREF="node5.html#Def._I">10</A>) is a
homogenous biideal in <!-- MATH
 ${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img191.png"
 ALT="${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$"> generated by the coideal <IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img202.png"
 ALT="$K_2$">.</DIV><P></P>

<P>
P<SMALL>ROOF: </SMALL>First we show that <IMG
 WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img201.png"
 ALT="$I$"> is a homogenous ideal. To this claim take
<IMG
 WIDTH="61" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img203.png"
 ALT="$a \in K_r$"> and <!-- MATH
 $b \in{{\cal E}_{u}}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="62" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img204.png"
 ALT="$b \in{{\cal E}_{u}}^*$">. We have to show 
<!-- MATH
 $a \otimes b \in K_{r+u}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="111" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img205.png"
 ALT="$a \otimes b \in K_{r+u}$"> and <!-- MATH
 $b \otimes a \in K_{r+u}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="111" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img206.png"
 ALT="$b \otimes a \in K_{r+u}$">. The choice of the element
<IMG
 WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img169.png"
 ALT="$a$"> can be reduced to a generator <!-- MATH
 $a={\vartheta}_{tr}([\mu,\nu])$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="118" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img207.png"
 ALT="$a={\vartheta}_{tr}([\mu,\nu])$"> of the <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">-module <IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img188.png"
 ALT="$K_r$">
with <!-- MATH
 $\mu 
\in{\cal E}_r$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="57" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img208.png"
 ALT="$\mu
\in{\cal E}_r$"> and <!-- MATH
 $\nu \in {\cal A}_r$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="61" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img209.png"
 ALT="$\nu \in {\cal A}_r$">.
Letting 
<!-- MATH
 $\hat{\nu}:=s_{r+u-1} \circ s_{r+u-2} \circ \ldots \circ s_{r}(\nu) =
\nu \otimes {\rm id}_{V^{\otimes u}} \in {\cal A}_{r+u}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="433" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img210.png"
 ALT="$\hat{\nu}:=s_{r+u-1} \circ s_{r+u-2} \circ \ldots \circ s_{r}(\nu) =
\nu \otimes {\rm id}_{V^{\otimes u}} \in {\cal A}_{r+u}$"> and
<!-- MATH
 $\hat\mu :=\mu \otimes \bar b$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="89" HEIGHT="40" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img211.png"
 ALT="$\hat\mu :=\mu \otimes \bar b$">, where <!-- MATH
 $\bar b\in {\cal E}_{u}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="55" HEIGHT="40" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img212.png"
 ALT="$\bar b\in {\cal E}_{u}$"> is the preimage of <IMG
 WIDTH="13" HEIGHT="19" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img213.png"
 ALT="$b$">
under <!-- MATH
 ${\vartheta}_{tr}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img18.png"
 ALT="${\vartheta}_{tr}$"> one obtains
<BR><P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
a \otimes b = {\vartheta}_{tr}([\mu,\nu]) \otimes b = {\vartheta}_{tr}([\hat\mu ,\hat{\nu}]) \in
K_{r+u}.
\end{displaymath}
 -->

<IMG
 WIDTH="453" HEIGHT="33" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img214.png"
 ALT="\begin{displaymath}a \otimes b = {\vartheta}_{tr}([\mu,\nu]) \otimes b = {\vartheta}_{tr}([\hat\mu ,\hat{\nu}]) \in
K_{r+u}.\end{displaymath}">
</DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL">
<P></P>
Similary <!-- MATH
 $b \otimes a \in K_{r+u}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="111" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img206.png"
 ALT="$b \otimes a \in K_{r+u}$"> and the first statement is
established.
<BR>
<P>
For the second part denote by <IMG
 WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img125.png"
 ALT="$J$"> the homogenous ideal in
<!-- MATH
 ${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img191.png"
 ALT="${\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)$"> generated by <IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img202.png"
 ALT="$K_2$">. Since <IMG
 WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img201.png"
 ALT="$I$"> is a homogenous ideal
containing <IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img202.png"
 ALT="$K_2$"> we get <IMG
 WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img215.png"
 ALT="$J\subseteq I$">. For the reverse inclusion we
show <!-- MATH
 $K_r\subseteq J$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="65" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img216.png"
 ALT="$K_r\subseteq J$"> by induction on <IMG
 WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img177.png"
 ALT="$r$">. Clearly
<IMG
 WIDTH="126" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img217.png"
 ALT="$K_0=K_1=(0)$"> and <IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img202.png"
 ALT="$K_2$"> are contained in <IMG
 WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img125.png"
 ALT="$J$">. Now suppose <IMG
 WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img218.png"
 ALT="$r&gt;2$">.
Letting <!-- MATH
 $J_r:=J\cap{{\cal E}_r}^*$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="111" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img219.png"
 ALT="$J_r:=J\cap{{\cal E}_r}^*$"> one obtains <!-- MATH
 $J_r=J_{r-1}\otimes {{\cal E}}^*+{{\cal E}}^*\otimes
J_{r-1}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="226" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img220.png"
 ALT="$J_r=J_{r-1}\otimes {{\cal E}}^*+{{\cal E}}^*\otimes
J_{r-1}$">. By induction hypothesis we see <!-- MATH
 $K_{r-1} = J_{r-1}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="105" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img221.png"
 ALT="$K_{r-1} = J_{r-1}$">. Therefore
<BR><P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
J_r=K_{r-1}\otimes {{\cal E}}^*+ {{\cal E}}^*\otimes K_{r-1}=
K(M)
\end{displaymath}
 -->

<IMG
 WIDTH="432" HEIGHT="33" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img222.png"
 ALT="\begin{displaymath}J_r=K_{r-1}\otimes {{\cal E}}^*+ {{\cal E}}^*\otimes K_{r-1}=
K(M) \end{displaymath}">
</DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL">
<P></P>
where <!-- MATH
 $M:=s_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1}) + t_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1}) \subseteq
{\cal E}_r$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="294" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img223.png"
 ALT="$M:=s_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1}) + t_{r-1}({\cal A}_{r-1}) \subseteq
{\cal E}_r$">. But since <IMG
 WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img224.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}_r$"> is generated by <IMG
 WIDTH="25" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img41.png"
 ALT="$M$"> as an algebra
we finally see from corollary <A HREF="node2.html#Verknupfungstreue">2.3</A>
<!-- MATH
 $K_r =K({\cal A}_r)=K(M)=J_r$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="227" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img225.png"
 ALT="$K_r =K({\cal A}_r)=K(M)=J_r$">.<IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img35.png"
 ALT="$\Box$">
<BR><P>
According to the proposition we may assign a
<EM>graded matric bialgebra</EM> to each subset <!-- MATH
 $N\subseteq {\cal E}_{2}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="65" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img195.png"
 ALT="$N\subseteq {\cal E}_{2}$"> by
<BR>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER"><A NAME="FRT_allgemein"></A>
<!-- MATH
 \begin{eqnarray}
{\cal M}(N):={\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)/I
\end{eqnarray}
 -->
<TABLE ALIGN="CENTER" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR VALIGN="MIDDLE"><TD NOWRAP ALIGN="RIGHT"><IMG
 WIDTH="158" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img226.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle {\cal M}(N):={\cal T}({{\cal E}}^*)/I$"></TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10 ALIGN="RIGHT">
(11)</TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL"><P></P>
whose homogenous summand are the centralizer coalgebras <IMG
 WIDTH="62" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img227.png"
 ALT="$M({\cal A}_r)$">.
This bialgebra will be called the <EM>FRT-construction</EM> corresponding
to the subset <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img56.png"
 ALT="$N$">. The reader familiar with the ordinary
FRT-construction will recognize the latter one as the special case
where <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img56.png"
 ALT="$N$"> consists of just one element <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img228.png"
 ALT="$\beta$"> (use the description
(<A HREF="node5.html#frt_konkret">12</A>) below). In this case we write
<!-- MATH
 ${\cal M}(\beta):={\cal M}(N)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="139" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img229.png"
 ALT="${\cal M}(\beta):={\cal M}(N)$">. Usually in the applications this <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img228.png"
 ALT="$\beta$"> is a
<EM>quantum Yang-Baxter operator</EM> leading to a representation of
the <EM>Artin braid groups</EM> on the modules <IMG
 WIDTH="37" HEIGHT="20" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img178.png"
 ALT="$V^{\otimes r}$">. In this situaton
the algebras <IMG
 WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img224.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}_r$"> are just the images of the corresponding
group algebras (over <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$R$">) under this representation.
<BR>
<P>
An application where <IMG
 WIDTH="22" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img56.png"
 ALT="$N$"> must consist of two elements will be given in
the next section. Here the <IMG
 WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img224.png"
 ALT="${\cal A}_r$"> are images of the <EM>Brauer
  centralizer algebras</EM> under Brauer's representations corresponding
to the symplectic groups. The bialgebra <IMG
 WIDTH="59" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img230.png"
 ALT="${\cal M}(N)$"> will turn out to be
the coordinate ring of a certain <EM>symplectic monoid</EM>.
It is a remarkable fact, that the second operator is only needed
in the classical situation, whereas in the quantum case it lies in the
algebraic span of the quantum Yang-Baxter operator (see [<A
 HREF="node9.html#doc">Oe</A>],
Bemerkung 2.5.1, 2.5.4). Thus, the ordinary FRT-construction behaves
singularly (in a certain sense) when specializing the deformation parameter
to 1, i.e. in the classical limit.
<BR>
<P>
